    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1918-01-07T09:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1918-01-07T09:00:00-05:00" n="17"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d17">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 600.119/476</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Great Britain</hi> (<persName
                        corresp="frus1918Supp01v01#p_PWH1" type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Page</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">London</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1918-01-07T14:00:00+00:00">
                            <hi rend="italic">January 7, 1918, 2 p.m.</hi>
                        </date>
                        <lb/> [<hi rend="italic">Received January 8, 1.08 a.m.</hi>]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>8170. For War Trade Board from <persName corresp="frus1918Supp01v01#p_SLP1"
                        >Sheldon</persName>:</p>
                <p>No. 7. Referring my telegram December 29 on possible relaxation embargo certain
                    articles Scandinavia, British Foreign Office write: <quote rend="blockquote">
                        <p>Suggest you notify your Government that in view of pressing importance of
                            countering German efforts to capture trade these <pb facs="0105" n="939"
                                xml:id="pg_939"/> countries and of improving his own exchange His
                            Majesty’s Government propose to issue, from January 15 next, license for
                            those goods which the conference recommend should be excepted from the
                            embargo unless before that date any objection is raised by the people of
                            the United States or any of the Allied Governments. Exports, when
                            resumed, will be subject to the same restrictions in respect to quantity
                            and consignees as they were previously to the imposition of the
                            embargo.</p>
                    </quote>
                </p>
                <p>Your early instructions are requested.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="frus1918Supp01v01#p_PWH1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Page</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
